  "text": "Emergence of bat rabies over the previous decades in Europe, North America, and quite recently in Australia, appears to be a discovery of an ancient infection rather than emergence of new virus or contemporary adaptation of virus to new hosts. In general, mortality in rabies-infected bats appears to be low, with seroconversion occurring in many surviving individuals [CITATION_1] . Bats appear to be the preferred hosts of many lyssaviruses, and many rabies viruses of terrestrial species may have originated in bats. Among the seven genotypes classically identified by cross immunity and monoclonal antibody typing, more recent molecular techniques have distinguished two phylogroups, the first encompassing classic rabies virus in terrestrial mammals (with several bat strains, including the Australian bat lyssavirus); the second comprises Lagos bat and Mokola viruses which are less pathogenic (5), although fatalities have been observed in the USA and Australia.",
